06745nam a22008295i 9780812298284DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222022pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122982847 a10.9783/97808122982842doi  a(DE-B1597)590448  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aJF801b.C5166 2022eb 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a323.622300aCitizenship on the Edge :bSex/Gender/Race /ced. by Nancy J. Hirschmann, Deborah A. Thomas. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (280 p.) :b15 b/w halftones, 4 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDemocracy, Citizenship, and Constitutionalism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. Citizenship on the Edge: Sex/Gender/Race -- t1. When Words Don’t Disappear: An Intersectional Analysis of Hate Speech -- t2. A Trinity of Inequality: Wealth, Marriage, and Masculinity -- t3. New-Old Law in the Postcolony: Regulating Sex in the Anglophone Caribbean -- t4. Institutional Changes and Women’s Citizenship in the Maghreb: Toward a New Gender Regime? -- t5. The Murder of Malcoum Tate: Madness, Violence, and Black Masculinity in the Late Twentieth-Century United States -- t6. From Anomaly to Alarm: Trans and Crip Bodies in the Security State -- t7. It’s Blue and It’s Up to You! Examining Federal Antitrafficking Awareness Campaigns in the United States -- t8. Reproductive Warfare: Enforced Sterilizations in Peru -- tAfterword. Citizenship on the Edge in the Age of COVID -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat does it mean to claim, two decades into the twenty-first century, that citizenship is on the edge? The questions that animate this volume focus attention on the relationships between liberal conceptions of citizenship and democracy on one hand, and sex, race, and gender on the other. Who "counts" as a citizen in today's world, and what are the mechanisms through which the rights, benefits, and protections of liberal citizenship are differentially bestowed upon diverse groups? What are the relationships between global economic processes and political and legal empowerment? What forms of violence emerge in order to defend and define these rights, benefits, and protections, and how do these forms of violence reflect long histories? How might we recognize and account for the various avenues through which people attempt to make themselves as political subjects?Citizenship on the Edge approaches these questions from multiple disciplines, including Africana Studies, anthropology, disability studies, film studies, gender studies, history, law, political science, and sociology. Contributors explore the ways in which compounding social inequalities redound to the conditions and expressions of citizenship in the U.S. and throughout the world. They give a sense of the breathtaking range of the ways that citizenship is controlled, repressed, undercut, and denied at the same time as they outline people's attempts to claim citizenship in ways that are meaningful to them. From university speech policies, to labor and immigration policies, to a rethinking of the security theatre, to women's empowerment in the family and economy and a rethinking of marriage and the family, we see slivers of possibility for a more inclusive and less hostile world, in which citizenship is no longer so in doubt, so on the edge, for so many. As a whole, the volume argues that citizenship cannot be conceptualized as a transcendent good but must instead always be contextualized within specific places and times, and in relation to dynamic struggle.Contributors: Erez Aloni, Ange-Marie Hancock Alfaro, Nancy J. Hirschmann, Samantha Majic, Valentine M. Moghadam, Michael Rembis, Tracy Robinson, Ellen Samuels, Kimberly Theidon, Deborah A. Thomas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCitizenshipxSocial aspects. 0aCitizenship. 0aMarginality, Social. 0aMinoritiesxCivil rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.1 aAloni, Erez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHancock Alfaro, Ange-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirschmann, Nancy J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHirschmann, Nancy J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMajic, Samantha, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoghadam, Valentine M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRembis, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobinson, Tracy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSamuels, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTheidon, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas, Deborah A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThomas, Deborah A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076767440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812298284423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812298284/original  a978-3-11-076767-4  University of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK